<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08164b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08164b">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08164b"> 164(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Salt for gods</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Popular Superstitions</b> And then, as to the spilling of salt, it was usual in certain paintings of the Last Supper to represent an overturned salt-cellar at Judas&apos;s elbow. This, however, would appear to be generally discredited; and the universally accepted origin lies in the fact that salt was formerly almost unobtainable, and consequently regarded by the ancient pagans as a meet offering to their gods. And the spilling of it, therefore, was looked upon as bound to incur their displeasure. <small> <a name="II9feb24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#II9feb24"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (9 February 1924) 5/3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
